---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
const title = 'Methodology | latepaycalc.com';
const description = 'How we calculate late-payment fees and interest: contract-specified rates, statutory defaults, usury cap checks, and state-specific employment penalties.';
---
<BaseLayout title={title} description={description}>
  <h1>Methodology</h1>
  <p>Our calculator handles two distinct late-payment contexts — B2B invoice / contract late fees and employment final-paycheck penalties — using different formulas. This page explains each step so you can verify every number the tool produces.</p>
  <p><em>Reviewed by Morgan Kettering (MK), Editor-in-Chief &amp; Wage Theft Lead, SHRM-SCP. Updated May 2026.</em></p>

  <h2>Step 1: Identify the scenario</h2>
  <p>The calculator asks you to choose between two modes:</p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>B2B invoice / contract</strong> — you're a vendor with an overdue customer invoice, or a contracting party owed payment under a written agreement. The relevant law is contract law plus state usury and commercial-interest statutes.</li>
    <li><strong>Employment final paycheck</strong> — you're a former employee whose final wages weren't paid on time, or an employer calculating your exposure. The relevant law is state wage-payment statutes, which impose their own penalties independent of contract terms.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>The two modes use different underlying formulas and pull from different legal authorities. Mixing them produces incorrect results — a California waiting-time penalty calculation has nothing to do with a contractual late-fee clause.</p>

  <h2>Step 2: Determine the applicable rate (B2B)</h2>
  <p>For B2B scenarios, rate priority works as follows:</p>
  <ol>
    <li><strong>Contractual rate.</strong> If your contract or invoice terms specify an annual interest rate (or a monthly rate — multiply by 12 to annualize), that rate applies, subject to the state usury cap check in Step 5. This is the strongest authority because the parties agreed to it.</li>
    <li><strong>State statutory commercial rate.</strong> If the contract is silent, most states allow creditors to recover interest at a statutory "commercial" or "legal" rate on overdue business debts. Typical range: 4–10% per year. Examples: California 10% (Cal. Civ. Code § 3289), New York 9% (CPLR § 5004), Texas 18% for written contracts (Tex. Fin. Code § 302.002).</li>
    <li><strong>Federal judgment rate as absolute fallback.</strong> If no state rate applies, the federal post-judgment interest rate (28 U.S.C. § 1961, keyed to weekly Treasury bill yields) provides a floor. This is rarely the operative rate in commercial disputes but exists as a backstop.</li>
  </ol>
  <p>Enter the rate you want to apply. If you're unsure of your state's statutory rate, the calculator defaults to 8% APR — a rough midpoint for illustration only, not legal advice on your state's actual rate.</p>

  <h2>Step 3: Apply the B2B late-fee formula</h2>
  <p>Once rate and flat fee are established, the formula is:</p>
  <p><code>Total late charge = Flat fee (if any) + (Amount overdue &times; (Annual rate &divide; 365) &times; Days late)</code></p>
  <p>This is simple interest — calculated on the original principal, not compounded. Compound interest is less common in late-fee contexts and may face stricter enforceability scrutiny (see <a href="/guides/how-late-pay-penalties-are-calculated">full formula guide</a>).</p>
  <p><strong>Worked example:</strong> $8,000 invoice, 60 days overdue, contract specifies $75 flat fee + 1.5%/month (18% APR) interest.</p>
  <ul>
    <li>Interest = $8,000 &times; (0.18 &divide; 365) &times; 60 = $236.71</li>
    <li>Total = $75 + $236.71 = <strong>$311.71</strong></li>
  </ul>
  <p>The flat fee applies once (at the trigger point). Interest accrues daily until paid.</p>

  <h2>Step 4: Apply the employment penalty formula</h2>
  <p>For employment final-paycheck scenarios, the formula depends on state. The most widely cited example is California's waiting-time penalty under Labor Code § 203:</p>
  <p><code>Penalty = Daily wage &times; Days late</code> (capped at 30 days)</p>
  <p>"Daily wage" is your regular daily rate of pay — hourly rate &times; hours per day, or annual salary &divide; 260 (52 weeks &times; 5 days), depending on your pay structure.</p>
  <p><strong>Worked example (California):</strong> Employee earns $280/day. Final paycheck is 20 days late. Penalty = $280 &times; 20 = $5,600. If it were 45 days late, the cap would limit penalty to $280 &times; 30 = $8,400.</p>
  <p>Other states use different structures:</p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Massachusetts:</strong> Triple (treble) damages on unpaid wages plus attorney's fees (M.G.L. c. 149, § 150). No day-cap — this multiplier can be substantial.</li>
    <li><strong>Illinois:</strong> 1% per day on unpaid wages plus attorney's fees (820 ILCS 115/14).</li>
    <li><strong>Texas:</strong> The lesser of treble damages or 4 weeks' wages for willful violations (Tex. Lab. Code § 61.018).</li>
    <li><strong>Most other states:</strong> Actual unpaid wages plus statutory damages, often 25–100% of unpaid amount, plus attorney's fees. The calculator uses the California formula by default; adjust for your state using the guides.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Step 5: Apply the usury cap check (B2B)</h2>
  <p>Even when parties have agreed to a contractual rate, state usury laws impose ceilings. Exceeding the ceiling can render the excess interest unenforceable — and in some states, all interest.</p>
  <p>Key nuances:</p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Consumer vs. commercial transactions.</strong> Consumer transactions (credit cards, personal loans) face stricter caps. Many states exempt commercial transactions entirely from usury limits or allow much higher caps for written commercial agreements.</li>
    <li><strong>Amount thresholds.</strong> Some states (e.g., New York) exempt loans above a certain principal amount from usury ceilings under commercial exception rules.</li>
    <li><strong>Choice of law.</strong> If your contract specifies another state's law, that state's usury limit may govern — though courts sometimes won't honor this if it's an attempt to evade a lower local cap.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>The calculator does not dynamically apply state usury caps — those require legal analysis of your specific contract and jurisdiction. If you're setting a rate, verify it's within your state's commercial ceiling before using it in a contract or claiming it against a customer.</p>

  <h2>Step 6: Interpret the result</h2>
  <p>The calculator output is an estimate for planning purposes only. It is not a legal determination of what you're owed or what is enforceable. Factors the calculator doesn't account for:</p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Compound interest.</strong> Most late-fee scenarios use simple interest. The calculator always uses simple interest.</li>
    <li><strong>Partial payments.</strong> If the debtor paid part of the balance, adjust the "Amount overdue" input accordingly.</li>
    <li><strong>Disputed invoices.</strong> If the customer has raised a timely, good-faith dispute, late fees may not accrue during the dispute period under some state laws.</li>
    <li><strong>Bankruptcy stay.</strong> If the debtor is in bankruptcy, collection actions — including interest accrual — may be stayed under 11 U.S.C. § 362.</li>
    <li><strong>FCRA and debt-collection laws.</strong> Reporting or collecting a debt triggers additional federal and state requirements not modeled here.</li>
    <li><strong>Attorney's fees provisions.</strong> Many state wage statutes and some commercial contracts allow fee-shifting. Those amounts aren't modeled.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>For any dispute involving meaningful money, consult a licensed attorney in your state. See our <a href="/guides/">guides</a> for background reading before that conversation.</p>
</BaseLayout>
